-[Tom] <i>Sasha. It's me, Tom.</i>

17:03.522 --> 17:04.982
Hello, Mr. President.

17:05.065 --> 17:07.401
I am so sorry for everything
that you're dealing with.

17:07.484 --> 17:10.529
Well, the suddenness along with
the almost surreal invasiveness,

17:10.612 --> 17:12.448
it has been a bit disorienting.

17:12.531 --> 17:13.741
It's appalling.

17:13.824 --> 17:16.910
It didn't occur to me that running
for a second term would bring this on.

17:16.994 --> 17:19.621
-[Sasha]<i> And so it has.</i>
-Right.

17:20.789 --> 17:23.500
Well, now I find myself
in the awkward position

17:23.584 --> 17:26.336
<i>of having to ask you if you'd be</i>
<i>willing to come to Washington, DC.</i>

17:26.420 --> 17:28.297
To help you politically?

17:28.380 --> 17:29.798
<i>No, to help us both. </i>

17:30.382 --> 17:33.886
I'm told that the only way to stop
this intrusion into your private life

17:33.969 --> 17:36.513
<i>is for us to stand together,</i>
<i>a public appearance.</i>

17:36.597 --> 17:41.143
I need to relinquish my privacy
in order to restore it?

17:41.226 --> 17:46.023
[sighs] I'm afraid so.
Obviously, the choice is yours.

17:48.901 --> 17:51.236
I'll catch the first flight out
in the morning.

17:51.320 --> 17:55.365
Okay. Thank you, Sasha. I'll see you soon.

17:55.949 --> 17:56.950
Good night, Tom.

18:03.791 --> 18:06.543
So I just wanted to let you
and everyone at the <i>Post</i> know

18:06.627 --> 18:09.588
that all campaign-related questions
should now be directed my way.

18:09.671 --> 18:13.175
And as for trading leaks
for favorable coverage,

18:13.258 --> 18:15.010
heaven forfend.

18:15.594 --> 18:16.595
Bye, Howard.

18:18.889 --> 18:21.600
-What's up? You miss me already?
-Oh. Envious.

18:22.559 --> 18:24.728
But I decided that, as always,

18:24.812 --> 18:27.523
jealousy is stupid,
when I could just join you.

18:28.816 --> 18:32.694
-I can't poach you from Seth.
-That's a little plantationy, no?

18:33.695 --> 18:36.657
Well, he's a friend,
and he raves about you.

18:36.740 --> 18:39.576
-[Lorraine] What? What?
-What?

18:39.660 --> 18:43.372
The FCC just ruled that our convention
is not a convention, it's a rally,

18:43.455 --> 18:46.500
and thus not entitled to free air time
on the networks.

18:46.583 --> 18:48.669
We would have to pay
for four days of coverage,

18:48.752 --> 18:50.629
which we cannot afford to do.

18:50.712 --> 18:53.132
Take a wild guess
who first appointed the commissioner

18:53.215 --> 18:55.259
-who cast the swing vote.
-Moss.

18:55.342 --> 18:59.596
Are you starting to understand what kind
of a dick we're dealing with, Pollyanna?

19:01.473 --> 19:05.602
Stage it someplace cool and free.
And put it on the Web.

19:05.686 --> 19:09.148
-You're the White House digital guy.
-I guess.

19:09.231 --> 19:12.985
So an unconvention? That could work.

19:15.279 --> 19:17.865
You work here now, for her. Set it up.

19:20.534 --> 19:22.661
-Sir.
-[Tom] Aaron, please.

19:22.744 --> 19:25.914
I intended to get to this earlier,
but it's been a day.

19:25.998 --> 19:27.457
Well, aren't they all?

19:27.541 --> 19:30.586
It's a wonder anybody even wants this job,
let alone chases after it

19:30.669 --> 19:33.005
as hard as I'm learning you have to,
to get it.

19:33.672 --> 19:37.009
Anyway, I wanted to talk to you
about something.

19:38.594 --> 19:40.470
Something rather momentous.

19:41.180 --> 19:42.097
Sir.

19:43.098 --> 19:44.099
Syria.

19:44.808 --> 19:46.393
[stutters] Sir?

19:46.476 --> 19:50.981
I want you to quietly, secretly reach out
to the parties involved in the conflict,

19:51.064 --> 19:54.610
with an eye not just towards
a cessation of hostilities,

19:54.693 --> 19:57.446
but a realistic, workable peace plan.

19:57.529 --> 20:00.449
Syria is quickly becoming
a potential tinderbox for World War III,

20:00.532 --> 20:04.620
and we have to do absolutely everything
we can to solve this before it's too late.

20:04.703 --> 20:06.455
It will be an honor to try.

20:10.000 --> 20:13.795
-Was there anything else?
-[chuckles] No. Isn't that enough?

20:14.755 --> 20:17.216
-Right. Thank you, Mr. President.
-Come on.

20:21.011 --> 20:22.095
[sniffles]

20:26.308 --> 20:30.229
-Sorry to be late.
-That was for you. I'm used to it.

20:31.063 --> 20:33.357
Quite all right.
Please, sit down, Mr. Harper.

20:35.275 --> 20:39.988
Okay, well,
the purpose of today's session is to--

20:40.072 --> 20:41.448
Our second go-around.

20:42.115 --> 20:45.619
You wanna know what in our relationship
might help account for my being here.

20:46.328 --> 20:48.413
-Is that what you want to discuss today?
-Let her--

20:48.497 --> 20:50.207
He's a wonderful partner.

20:50.290 --> 20:55.837
He's attentive and irreproachable
and unimpeachably correct.

20:55.921 --> 20:57.756
She doesn't mean that as a compliment.

20:58.340 --> 21:00.884
I noticed that you didn't say loving.

21:02.803 --> 21:04.805
It's not applicable.

21:05.389 --> 21:08.642
-That's unfair.
-Our marriage was transactional.

21:08.725 --> 21:10.310
There's no shame in it.

21:10.394 --> 21:13.021
There's just no sense
in pretending otherwise.

21:13.105 --> 21:14.189
Transactional in what way?

21:14.273 --> 21:18.277
She means I'm the poor-boy grocer's son
who married into her money.

21:19.820 --> 21:23.865
Money was incidental.
He married me for my father.

21:23.949 --> 21:26.201
And your father
was a prominent politician?

21:27.828 --> 21:29.705
He was the "Lion of the Senate."

21:31.707 --> 21:34.334
Just the ticket
for an ambitious young climber

21:34.418 --> 21:37.504
with a degree in political science
from a mediocre university.

21:38.880 --> 21:42.009
Earlier, you said that your husband
was irreproachable.

21:46.972 --> 21:52.019
Do you know he's never smoked pot?
Or whatever they call it these days.

21:52.894 --> 21:56.106
It took me the longest time
to decide if that was, uh...

21:57.316 --> 22:00.694
discipline, timidity,

22:00.777 --> 22:04.489
or just the avoidance
of a biographical detail

22:04.573 --> 22:07.284
that might jeopardize
his professional ascent.

22:07.868 --> 22:09.703
And did you arrive at any conclusions?

22:11.580 --> 22:16.626
-[chuckles] It was an implied rebuke.
-In other words, this is all my fault.

22:18.462 --> 22:19.463
Not all.

22:24.676 --> 22:25.927
But not none.

22:30.640 --> 22:34.061
I'm there waiting for him
to bring up the VP slot.

22:34.144 --> 22:36.646
And it hit me, "Idiot!"
I told her I'd think about it.

22:36.730 --> 22:37.981
So have you?

22:38.065 --> 22:41.318
[Aaron] Well, it is the second
most powerful position in the free world.

22:41.401 --> 22:43.945
Oh. This morning it was
"a bucket of warm piss."

22:44.029 --> 22:47.115
Well, my views on the subject
are evolving.

22:47.199 --> 22:48.116
On the office, or wanting it?

22:48.200 --> 22:51.620
You said it would instantly make me
a plausible presidential contender.

22:51.703 --> 22:52.996
It's something I've never dreamt of.

22:53.080 --> 22:55.082
An opportunity
that might never come again.

22:55.165 --> 22:56.124
But?

22:56.208 --> 22:58.502
You and Lorraine
and, for all I know, the president,

22:58.585 --> 23:00.462
want me to be the Great Latino Hope.

23:00.545 --> 23:01.505
Which you're not okay with.

23:01.588 --> 23:03.131
I've been looking
to avoid that all my life.

23:03.215 --> 23:06.718
-And I know you don't agree with that--
-It's not for me to agree or disagree.

23:06.802 --> 23:09.012
Just stop, okay?
Just tell me what you think.

23:09.096 --> 23:13.058
I think you're a grown-ass man
and that your identity,

23:13.141 --> 23:15.977
and your relationship to it,
is something you worked out for yourself

23:16.061 --> 23:18.522
a long time ago and will survive

23:18.605 --> 23:21.650
whatever external objectification you
might be in for in a national campaign.

23:21.733 --> 23:24.861
-Yeah, "might be"?
-Will be. My point stands.

23:27.114 --> 23:30.534
-[sighs] All right.
-Holy shit, is this really happening?

23:31.076 --> 23:35.122
[clears throat] Lorraine.
Hey, sorry to bother you so late. I...

23:35.997 --> 23:39.042
I guess it's your voice mail,
so this is not really, uh...

23:39.126 --> 23:41.503
Look, I just wanted to touch base...

23:41.586 --> 23:44.464
[stuttering] Yeah,
not touch base so much as...

23:44.548 --> 23:45.674
Oh, my God.

23:45.757 --> 23:49.177
Look, I wanted to call you
to tell you... Shit.

23:49.261 --> 23:51.888
Smooth. Really, I wouldn't change a word.

23:54.057 --> 23:56.268
What? You gotta be shitting...
Her mailbox is full.

23:56.351 --> 23:58.270
-Well, text her.
-I'm not gonna text her.

23:58.353 --> 24:00.522
You don't accept a VP nod
via text message.

24:00.605 --> 24:02.566
E-mail, then. Whatever, baby.
Just get it done.

24:02.649 --> 24:04.276
What do you want me to do?
Do you want me--

24:04.359 --> 24:05.694
[cell phone ringing]

24:09.489 --> 24:10.490
Lorraine.

24:11.992 --> 24:15.162
Okay, this is doable. Yeah?

24:15.745 --> 24:18.165
An unconvention
for the accidental president.

24:18.248 --> 24:21.501
-It's not just doable, it's almost cool.
-Almost.

24:22.127 --> 24:23.003
It's still politics.

24:23.837 --> 24:26.715
-Hey, do you think I'm naive?
-That Pollyanna crack?

24:27.382 --> 24:28.425
Consider the source.

24:28.508 --> 24:31.011
Lorraine is a pro,
and that wasn't really an answer.

24:32.637 --> 24:35.599
-You have principles.
-Mmm. So in other words, yes.

24:36.433 --> 24:38.268
Having principles doesn't make you naive.

24:38.351 --> 24:41.104
[sighs] I probably need to
toughen up a little.

24:45.275 --> 24:48.612
<i>He thought he could keep it</i>
<i>hidden away, lurking. </i>

24:48.695 --> 24:51.865
<i>And then spring it</i>
<i>on an unsuspecting American public,</i>

24:51.948 --> 24:56.328
<i>a radical, alt-gender,</i>
<i>alt-sexuality agenda.</i>

24:56.411 --> 24:59.414
<i>It's such an out-of-sight-out-of-mind,</i>
<i>back-in-the-closet marginalization. </i>

24:59.497 --> 25:02.000
<i>Pretend she doesn't exist</i>
<i>and wish it into oblivion.</i>

25:03.627 --> 25:06.630
The right gets angry,
and the left gets sad.

25:07.297 --> 25:08.924
We need to seize the news cycle back.

25:09.007 --> 25:11.468
We're gonna do this unconvention thing,
but move it up.

25:11.551 --> 25:12.802
-[Lorraine] To?
-Tomorrow night.

25:12.886 --> 25:13.970
That's impossible.

25:14.054 --> 25:15.263
Sasha lands today.

25:15.347 --> 25:18.266
We do a photo op, then we change the story
right back to what we're running on.

25:18.350 --> 25:19.392
That should work.

25:19.476 --> 25:21.770
If it were workable.
There are logistics involved.

25:21.853 --> 25:24.022
Like what? All we need are cameras
and an Internet connection.

25:24.105 --> 25:26.107
I can't pull together a crowd
that quickly.

25:26.191 --> 25:29.986
We don't need one. That's the point.
I talk directly to the voter, personally.

25:30.070 --> 25:32.656
-Well, what about your speech?
-Pull an all-nighter.

25:34.032 --> 25:37.661
Uh, the story just broke
about Moss carrying the Alzheimer's gene.

25:37.744 --> 25:38.578
What?

25:39.371 --> 25:42.832
-Did I not make myself perfectly clear?
-I didn't do this.

25:42.916 --> 25:44.751
You got 30 seconds
to make me believe that.

25:44.834 --> 25:47.921
Hey, I know that you and, you know,
Jiminy Cricket here

25:48.004 --> 25:51.591
think that I would do anything to win,
and, okay, you're right, I would,

25:51.675 --> 25:56.012
right up to ignoring explicit, unambiguous
instructions from my candidate,

25:56.096 --> 25:59.015
which I have never done
and would never do.

25:59.099 --> 26:01.518
Because you do it once,
you can kiss your career goodbye.

26:01.601 --> 26:04.604
This wasn't me.
Polygraph me on a stack of Bibles,

26:04.688 --> 26:06.856
holding a gun to my dog's
and my mother's head.

26:08.191 --> 26:09.609
Someone at the lab, maybe?

26:09.693 --> 26:11.444
We'll deal with it later,
but we are definitely doing this.

26:11.528 --> 26:14.197
We are gonna steal the news cycle
back from this shit.

26:22.163 --> 26:26.626
-The flu hit roughly three weeks ago.
-Isolated to this clinic?

26:26.710 --> 26:28.336
[Eli] Mortality rate, Dr. Mouray?

26:28.420 --> 26:33.049
Zero. People got pretty intense symptoms.
I caught it, and it kicked my butt.

26:33.675 --> 26:35.176
[Hannah] That's scary, in your condition.

26:35.760 --> 26:39.055
A bit. But two weeks later,
I was completely fine.

26:39.597 --> 26:40.682
Everyone was.

26:40.765 --> 26:43.351
I'm sorry there's nothing
more dramatic to report.

26:43.435 --> 26:47.814
Well, not sorry, obviously.
But you may have come up here for nothing.

26:47.897 --> 26:50.442
Have you identified a patient zero
for the outbreak?

26:50.525 --> 26:51.359
Not really.

26:51.443 --> 26:54.112
Anything unusual or different here
around that time?

26:54.195 --> 26:55.196
No.

26:56.281 --> 26:58.283
We did hire this new nurse.

26:58.825 --> 27:02.912
-I'll need to speak to him or her.
-Mmm-hmm. A guy. But he quit.

27:02.996 --> 27:05.665
Then I'll need
his contact information, please.

27:06.249 --> 27:08.543
And we have clear statutory authority

27:08.626 --> 27:10.378
to strong-arm
these drug companies on this?

27:10.462 --> 27:12.881
I checked with Counsel's office.
They signed off.

27:12.964 --> 27:14.007
But my only question is,

27:14.090 --> 27:16.009
this law has been on the books
for decades.

27:16.092 --> 27:18.178
-Why has no administration tried this?
-You know why.

27:18.887 --> 27:21.473
President's willing to tick off Big Pharma
in an election year?

27:21.556 --> 27:24.392
-He wants to govern.
-Plus, he can run on this.

27:24.476 --> 27:27.103
We need to find the exact right test case.

27:27.187 --> 27:30.857
A medication way too expensive
for something common and serious.

27:30.940 --> 27:34.235
Preferably where people have died.
I am going to hell.

27:34.319 --> 27:36.071
Heaven, anyone asks me.

27:36.738 --> 27:37.614
Insulin.

27:37.697 --> 27:41.618
Helmdale Pharmaceuticals has raised
their price eight-fold in the last decade,

27:41.701 --> 27:46.039
leading some diabetics
to ration their dosage with fatal results.

27:46.122 --> 27:47.749
Get the CEO in here.

27:47.832 --> 27:49.417
I will coordinate with your office
on a time.

27:49.501 --> 27:52.045
This is your project.
You bring this guy in.

27:52.837 --> 27:53.838
Yes, sir.

27:56.966 --> 27:57.967
[Tom] Oolong.

27:58.676 --> 28:01.304
-[Sasha] You remembered.
-Of course.

28:04.140 --> 28:06.518
So, tell me, how is Penny?

28:08.019 --> 28:11.064
Evidently she had
her first period yesterday.

28:11.981 --> 28:13.149
"Evidently"?

28:13.233 --> 28:16.027
The school didn't have her mother
to call anymore, so...

28:16.111 --> 28:19.114
So they called her father, the president.

28:19.197 --> 28:21.241
Worse, they left a message.

28:22.117 --> 28:25.703
Oh, how awful. Have you spoken to her?

28:25.787 --> 28:28.081
Not yet.
She stayed at a friend's house last night.

28:28.164 --> 28:29.499
Poor thing.

28:30.792 --> 28:33.378
I'd be happy to speak with her,
if you like.

28:34.295 --> 28:35.964
I don't know. I can...

28:37.257 --> 28:41.344
It's okay. You're correct.
I didn't actually go through it myself.

28:41.428 --> 28:44.305
It only felt like I did.

28:45.140 --> 28:47.100
But that's the whole point.

28:48.518 --> 28:50.395
But don't you think
that she'd be more comfortable

28:50.478 --> 28:54.190
discussing it with someone
who looks like me rather than like you?

28:54.816 --> 28:57.819
-Maybe you're right. Thank you.
-Yeah.

29:00.405 --> 29:03.533
I made a decision on the flight here

29:04.159 --> 29:07.537
that I not be employed as simply a prop.

29:07.620 --> 29:10.582
-Sasha, when I asked you to come--
-No, Tom, let me finish.

29:12.375 --> 29:15.044
Now that the things are as they are,

29:16.087 --> 29:19.299
there's no reason for me
to continue to absent myself

29:19.382 --> 29:23.553
from this place,
from a young girl who's lost her mother.

29:24.512 --> 29:26.389
So, unless you object,

29:26.473 --> 29:29.851
after we do the photo op
and wave from the balcony,

29:30.602 --> 29:33.730
I'd like to remain on, for her...

29:35.148 --> 29:37.150
and for Alex.

29:38.902 --> 29:41.112
Thank you. Penny would love that.

29:43.114 --> 29:44.115
And you?

29:44.699 --> 29:45.700
Of course.

29:47.660 --> 29:51.247
You know,
you never asked me any questions.

29:51.331 --> 29:53.374
Like, about my transition.

29:53.458 --> 29:57.295
I mean, everyone has questions.
You must have had some.

29:57.378 --> 29:59.756
I wanted to respect your privacy.

30:01.341 --> 30:07.680
So, tell me,
how do you feel, personally, about me?

30:08.389 --> 30:09.974
Completely accepting.

30:11.351 --> 30:14.813
Intellectually, sure.
But what about viscerally?

30:14.896 --> 30:18.566
I mean,
have you fully accepted it viscerally?

30:19.108 --> 30:21.277
Be truthful. Please.

30:22.737 --> 30:23.863
Honestly...

30:27.367 --> 30:29.410
I'd have to say that, viscerally...

30:32.163 --> 30:34.415
I'm still a work-in-progress.

30:38.253 --> 30:39.295
Aren't we all?

30:40.380 --> 30:42.257
I'm not sure why this is necessary.

30:42.340 --> 30:45.426
I've been extensively vetted
many times over for my previous positions.

30:45.510 --> 30:47.262
This is different, a political vetting.

30:47.345 --> 30:50.390
You'll be asked about more personal
information than for your previous posts.

30:50.473 --> 30:52.809
-Shall we begin?
-Yes, by all means.

30:53.393 --> 30:55.353
You've had an extensive bachelorhood.

30:55.436 --> 30:58.523
Has it resulted
in any sexually transmitted diseases?

30:58.606 --> 31:01.734
[laughs] Okay.
Talk about starting off with a bang.

31:05.196 --> 31:06.781
-No.
-No herpes?

31:06.865 --> 31:08.366
-HIV?
-No means no.

31:09.742 --> 31:12.078
Have you had sexual relations
with underage girls?

31:12.912 --> 31:13.746
Absolutely not.

31:13.830 --> 31:14.956
-Underage boys?
-No.

31:15.039 --> 31:16.416
-[Gwen] Men?
-No.

31:16.499 --> 31:18.835
Have you had sexual relations
with married women?

31:19.669 --> 31:22.380
Technically, yes.
She was separated at the time.

31:22.463 --> 31:24.173
We'll need her name
and contact information.

31:24.257 --> 31:26.259
-Why would that be necessary?
-For confirmation.

31:26.342 --> 31:27.927
But I already explained the circumstances.

31:28.011 --> 31:29.470
Then why object
to obtaining corroboration?

31:29.554 --> 31:31.681
'Cause she's not the one
being considered for office, I am.

31:31.764 --> 31:33.725
She deserves having her privacy respected.

31:33.808 --> 31:37.186
Anyone you've had intimacies with,
gotten drunk, high, gambled

31:37.270 --> 31:40.231
or broken the speed limit with you
on land, sea or air

31:40.315 --> 31:41.774
is fair game in this inquiry.

31:43.359 --> 31:44.694
Privacy be damned.

31:45.320 --> 31:46.738
In a word, yes.

31:50.867 --> 31:52.911
[line ringing]

31:53.578 --> 31:54.412
Hello?

31:55.038 --> 31:59.626
Hi. This is Seth Wright. I'm your...
You contacted me?

32:00.960 --> 32:02.754
I wasn't sure you'd respond.

32:02.837 --> 32:07.216
No, no, of course.
I'm really glad you reached out.

32:07.300 --> 32:10.261
Are you?
I didn't want it to be weird for you.

32:10.345 --> 32:13.848
-No, no, no. Not at all.
-Well, probably a little.

32:13.932 --> 32:16.643
[Seth] <i>Maybe. But also,</i>
<i>you know, kind of...</i>

32:16.726 --> 32:19.938
[scoffs] I'm trying to find
a less lame word for "cool."

32:20.688 --> 32:23.566
[chuckles] "Cool" is fine.
I think so, too.

32:24.233 --> 32:26.653
So, uh, do you wanna meet?

32:26.736 --> 32:31.491
Maybe grab a... I guess a drink might be
a little weird, but not illegal.

32:32.283 --> 32:36.287
-Let's have that drink.
-Great. How's tomorrow evening?

32:36.371 --> 32:37.330
[Stephanie] <i>Tomorrow's good.</i>

32:37.413 --> 32:41.417
Great. I just said "great."
At least I've moved on from "cool."

32:41.501 --> 32:43.544
[both chuckle]

32:43.628 --> 32:47.548
-Uh... Okay, so tomorrow, then?
-Tomorrow.

32:47.632 --> 32:49.968
All right. I'll text you.

32:50.051 --> 32:51.761
-[Stephanie]<i> Bye.</i>
-Bye.

33:00.812 --> 33:02.605
I can feel you watching me.

33:03.314 --> 33:04.315
Sorry.

33:05.858 --> 33:07.819
[sighs] No, I'm not.

33:07.902 --> 33:10.071
This is the most important speech
of my career.

33:10.154 --> 33:11.489
Until the next one.

33:13.741 --> 33:16.369
-Take a walk, sir.
-Fine.

33:23.960 --> 33:27.213
-[Penny chuckling]
-[Sasha] This is true. This is true.

33:28.339 --> 33:30.383
[Penny] I know! It's the worst.

33:30.466 --> 33:32.093
[Sasha] No. No, no, no, no.

33:32.176 --> 33:34.637
Actually, I have it on good authority
from your mom,

33:34.721 --> 33:38.433
-childbirth is the worst.
-Oh, God. Don't tell me that.

33:38.516 --> 33:41.602
But Leo's, not yours.
Evidently you were a breeze.

33:41.686 --> 33:43.604
She said she could've squatted in a field

33:43.688 --> 33:45.898
-and you would've popped right out.
-That's disgusting.

33:45.982 --> 33:48.317
-[Sasha] No, it's beautiful.
-[Penny] That's so gross.

33:48.401 --> 33:50.361
It's kind of gross. It's kind of gross.

33:50.445 --> 33:51.821
[Penny chuckling]

33:53.573 --> 33:54.574
So?

33:56.451 --> 33:58.953
It hits all the points
you've talked about.

34:00.288 --> 34:01.205
But?

34:02.123 --> 34:04.375
They're all things
other candidates have said.

34:04.459 --> 34:07.545
What can you tell voters
that they haven't already heard?

34:07.628 --> 34:11.883
What have you been thinking about that
wasn't on some memo from the policy shop?

34:20.558 --> 34:21.726
I know what it is.

34:31.486 --> 34:36.157
Hey. There's no trace of this male nurse.
He just blew in from nowhere.

34:36.240 --> 34:39.660
He's got a fake name, false credentials,
bogus references,

34:39.744 --> 34:41.204
and then he just ghosted.

34:41.287 --> 34:43.873
He could be a candidate
for who infected them all.

34:43.956 --> 34:45.291
I examined the virus.

34:45.374 --> 34:47.710
Entirely different
than what killed the birds,

34:47.794 --> 34:50.505
and no smallpox-derived contagion piece.

34:50.588 --> 34:51.756
So it could be a natural outbreak?

34:51.839 --> 34:54.675
No. There was something
CRISPR'd into the virus.

34:54.759 --> 34:56.552
I just don't recognize what it is.

34:59.138 --> 35:02.433
There's something else.
Dr. Mouray's office called.

35:03.392 --> 35:06.020
-She miscarried.
-Oh, my God.

35:06.104 --> 35:08.815
As did several other pregnant patients
who also got sick.

35:08.898 --> 35:11.734
-Can a bad flu do that?
-Up to a point.

35:12.443 --> 35:16.072
But I ran the numbers. This is in excess
of what you'd expect to find.

35:17.490 --> 35:20.201
An induced miscarriage cluster

35:20.284 --> 35:23.454
camouflaged to mimic something
that might occur naturally.

35:23.538 --> 35:26.707
What connects miscarriages in Canada
to dead birds in Florida?

35:27.583 --> 35:28.584
Maybe nothing.

35:29.710 --> 35:30.711
Maybe not.

35:32.630 --> 35:33.506
[Aaron] Sir.

35:34.632 --> 35:36.843
One of the nice things
about being president,

35:37.718 --> 35:39.929
no one tells you
you look like shit in the morning.

35:40.012 --> 35:43.141
[chuckles] I'm gonna observe
that tradition. Trouble sleeping?

35:43.224 --> 35:46.644
Up late working on the speech for tonight,
which is why I asked you here.

35:46.727 --> 35:50.982
I would like to begin with an announcement
of my running mate,

35:51.065 --> 35:52.859
and I would like that to be you.

35:53.568 --> 35:54.610
[exhales sharply]

35:55.945 --> 35:57.530
I'm deeply honored.

35:57.613 --> 35:58.698
Well, before you say that,

35:58.781 --> 36:01.826
I'd be remiss if I didn't warn you
about what you were getting into.

36:01.909 --> 36:02.910
[sighs]

36:03.536 --> 36:05.371
Absolute loss of privacy.

36:05.454 --> 36:08.541
In fact, in no way, shape or form
would your life be your own.

36:09.417 --> 36:10.585
I understand.

36:10.668 --> 36:12.920
No, you don't.
That's what I'm trying to convey.

36:14.797 --> 36:19.594
Sir, if it's not impertinent,
there is something I do have to ask you.

36:19.677 --> 36:20.720
Shoot.

36:20.803 --> 36:23.306
I need to know you're not choosing me
because I'm Latino.

36:25.474 --> 36:26.934
I respect the question.

36:28.227 --> 36:32.023
And I hope you'll respect my answer.

36:33.983 --> 36:37.028
The easiest thing for me to say
is that I hired the right man for the job,

36:37.111 --> 36:41.073
and as much as I believe that,
the honest answer is, I don't know.

36:42.408 --> 36:45.494
I'm not immune to the arguments
of an electoral advantage.

36:46.829 --> 36:48.456
But I can tell you this, Aaron.

36:48.539 --> 36:51.959
If at any point the campaign
were to treat your heritage

36:52.043 --> 36:53.920
in a way that made you uncomfortable,

36:54.587 --> 36:57.632
come to me, and I would make
an immediate course correction.

37:00.134 --> 37:01.636
I appreciate that, sir.

37:02.511 --> 37:05.014
And it would be
my great privilege to accept.

37:18.986 --> 37:22.281
Mr. Ralsch. Isabel Pardo.
Thank you for coming.

37:22.823 --> 37:23.908
Please.

37:25.243 --> 37:28.537
-The reason we invited you to--
-Are we waiting for Mr. Harper?

37:29.413 --> 37:30.873
You'll just be meeting with me.

37:35.086 --> 37:36.254
[clears throat]

37:38.547 --> 37:41.092
We are here to discuss march-in rights

37:41.175 --> 37:45.012
as applies to your Keziax brand
of insulin.

37:45.096 --> 37:46.389
As undoubtedly you know,

37:46.472 --> 37:48.933
Bayh-Dole allows for intervention
by the federal government--

37:49.016 --> 37:50.559
Purportedly allows.

37:51.227 --> 37:53.145
Quoting from the statute,

37:53.229 --> 37:56.023
"When action is necessary
to alleviate health needs

37:56.107 --> 37:57.733
which are not being
reasonably satisfied--"

37:57.817 --> 38:00.695
Our attorneys would engage
on the interpretation of "reasonably."

38:00.778 --> 38:05.074
And when the patented product
is not, again, quoting,

38:05.157 --> 38:07.618
"available to the public
on reasonable terms--"

38:07.702 --> 38:10.246
White House wants to dictate
how we conduct our business?

38:11.163 --> 38:15.584
Sir, I'm not here to deliver a lecture
on moral responsibility.

38:15.668 --> 38:16.502
[scoffs]

38:16.585 --> 38:19.338
[Isabel] I understand you have
an obligation to your shareholders,

38:19.422 --> 38:21.507
your board, your bottom line.

38:22.300 --> 38:24.593
I'm not gonna use charged language

38:24.677 --> 38:27.346
or make hand-wringing appeals
to a public good

38:27.430 --> 38:30.850
that's essentially an irrelevance
to the American pharmaceutical business.

38:30.933 --> 38:32.935
Well, that language
sounds charged enough to me.

38:33.644 --> 38:37.398
On the contrary, sir.
I didn't use words like "unconscionable,"

38:37.481 --> 38:41.694
"avaricious,"
or the term I use at home, "extortionate."

38:41.777 --> 38:43.529
[Ralsch] I believe we've heard enough.

38:44.405 --> 38:46.032
Due respect, sir, you haven't.

38:55.291 --> 39:00.087
<i>Our son Alec Smith, who would be 27,</i>
<i>is no longer with us. </i>

39:00.171 --> 39:03.215
<i>What I miss most about Alec</i>
<i>is his hugs and his smiles. </i>

39:03.299 --> 39:06.594
<i>He had the goofiest grin, </i>

39:06.677 --> 39:12.516
<i>but it was so original and so unique</i>
<i>that I miss seeing that grin. </i>

39:13.059 --> 39:16.020
<i>The official cause of death</i>
<i>on my son's death certificate </i>

39:16.103 --> 39:18.230
<i>is diabetic ketoacidosis. </i>

39:18.314 --> 39:21.150
<i>Unofficially, the cause of death</i>
<i>is corporate greed. </i>

39:21.776 --> 39:24.195
<i>Insulin was created almost 100 years ago. </i>

39:24.278 --> 39:26.697
<i>These insulin companies,</i>
<i>they got it for free, </i>

39:26.781 --> 39:31.410
<i>so every penny that they have made</i>
<i>off of insulin in almost 100 years</i>

39:31.494 --> 39:32.661
<i>has been profit.</i>

39:32.745 --> 39:37.333
<i>It costs $6 to create a vial of insulin,</i>

39:37.416 --> 39:39.877
<i>but they're selling it for almost $400.</i>

39:40.586 --> 39:41.921
<i>The price of his life. </i>

39:43.506 --> 39:48.469
<i>Alec died from rationing his insulin</i>
<i>because he couldn't afford it. </i>

39:48.552 --> 39:52.765
<i>Now I have to live the rest of my life</i>
<i>without my son. </i>

39:53.391 --> 39:58.813
<i>A part of my soul is gone</i>
<i>because the greedy people </i>

39:58.896 --> 40:03.901
<i>think that it's okay to randomly increase</i>
<i>the price of life-saving medications </i>

40:03.984 --> 40:05.277
<i>to the point where they're unaffordable</i>

40:05.361 --> 40:07.738
<i>for the people who need them</i>
<i>to stay alive.</i>

40:08.906 --> 40:12.076
<i>It's unfair, it's unethical</i>
<i>and it's unjust,</i>

40:12.159 --> 40:14.036
<i>and it needs to end.</i>

40:16.622 --> 40:19.834
So no other mother
has to needlessly lose a child

40:19.917 --> 40:22.962
due to the unaffordability
of your life-sustaining drugs,

40:23.504 --> 40:28.843
we suggest you lower the price to this.

40:28.926 --> 40:32.138
Or we take away your patent
and award it to a competitor,

40:32.721 --> 40:35.266
and release videos like these
justifying why.

40:39.603 --> 40:40.604
[indistinct chatter]

40:40.688 --> 40:42.648
-[Seth] Here we go.
-Thanks.

40:45.484 --> 40:47.695
I don't know how I feel
about you having a beer.

40:47.778 --> 40:49.321
-Seth.
-Not "Dad"?

40:50.656 --> 40:52.533
-Too soon.
-[chuckles]

40:52.616 --> 40:54.285
-Cheers.
-Cheers.

40:54.910 --> 40:56.787
Meet your daughter, day one. Here it is.

41:04.879 --> 41:06.005
[exhales heavily]

41:06.964 --> 41:08.841
It's showtime, Mr. President.

41:12.887 --> 41:13.721
[Tom] Thank you.

41:18.434 --> 41:19.310
[exhales heavily]

41:20.853 --> 41:26.025
When you're ready.
Five, four, three, two, and we're live.

41:26.609 --> 41:30.446
My fellow Americans,
wherever you are viewing this tonight,

41:30.529 --> 41:33.282
your options in this new era
seem limitless.

41:33.365 --> 41:36.994
So I have chosen to speak to you
in this less-than-traditional fashion,

41:37.077 --> 41:41.373
streaming via smartphone, laptop,
satellite or onto your television,

41:41.457 --> 41:43.792
because I want you
to understand that I am trying

41:43.876 --> 41:47.796
to talk to each and every one of you
personally, as my fellow citizen.

41:48.422 --> 41:51.967
Not to any special interest groups
or corporate America.

41:52.051 --> 41:54.637
<i>To begin, I'd like to tell you</i>
<i>that I have chosen</i>

41:54.720 --> 41:58.182
<i>National Security Advisor Aaron Shore</i>
<i>to be my candidate for vice president.</i>

41:58.265 --> 41:59.266
-Hi.
-[Mars] Hello.

41:59.350 --> 42:02.478
[Tom] <i>I am very proud to have Aaron</i>
<i>as my running mate.</i>

42:02.561 --> 42:05.105
-What did I miss?
-Just the VP announcement. Go.

42:08.359 --> 42:11.445
Detailed information
on all these proposals and more

42:11.529 --> 42:15.157
will be posted on our campaign website
immediately following this address.

42:16.492 --> 42:20.538
On a personal note, there is something
I would like you to reflect on.

42:21.205 --> 42:24.792
Recent days have seen
egregious violations of personal privacy

42:24.875 --> 42:27.628
involving my sister-in-law
and one of my opponents.

42:28.254 --> 42:30.881
These incidents are connected
to what I believe to be

42:30.965 --> 42:34.677
a general erosion
of the concept of personal privacy.

42:34.760 --> 42:38.347
Sometimes we, as citizens,
are all too often complicit

42:38.430 --> 42:42.768
in the erasing of boundaries between our
public and private lives via social media.

42:42.851 --> 42:46.855
And we may also find ourselves
unwitting and often unwilling captors

42:46.939 --> 42:49.942
to algorithms
that invasively track our every click.

42:50.526 --> 42:52.152
In consideration of this,

42:52.236 --> 42:55.239
I will ask Congress
to authorize a new cabinet office,

42:55.322 --> 42:57.950
the Department of Digital Technology,

42:58.033 --> 43:01.662
to bring enlightened oversight
to our now hyperconnected world.

43:02.413 --> 43:06.250
Via the Internet, it has become
too easy to stir anger and fear

43:06.333 --> 43:07.501
where none is deserved.

43:08.168 --> 43:10.671
<i>My sister-in-law</i>
<i>is a perfect example of that.</i>

43:11.338 --> 43:14.883
<i>Sasha isn't a symbol</i>
<i>for either the intolerant or the activist.</i>

43:15.509 --> 43:17.177
<i>She is a fellow American citizen,</i>

43:17.261 --> 43:19.263
<i>endowed with the same inalienable rights</i>

43:19.346 --> 43:22.391
<i>to life, liberty and the pursuit</i>
<i>of happiness as all of us.</i>

43:23.225 --> 43:27.271
<i>Now, I am not so naive as to believe</i>
<i>that simply because we are all Americans, </i>

43:27.354 --> 43:29.315
<i>we will all agree on every issue.</i>

43:29.898 --> 43:32.026
<i>But if history teaches us anything, </i>

43:32.109 --> 43:35.904
<i>it is that our country's ability to be</i>
<i>understanding and tolerant of each other</i>

43:35.988 --> 43:38.073
<i>has made us</i>
<i>one of the great shining lights</i>

43:38.157 --> 43:39.742
<i>for democracy and the world.</i>

43:40.659 --> 43:43.746
<i>We arrive at tolerance and acceptance</i>
<i>by varied paths. </i>

43:44.413 --> 43:48.876
<i>Some come by it as a matter of course,</i>
<i>and some through time and experience. </i>

43:48.959 --> 43:51.378
<i>I've been blessed</i>
<i>to have Sasha in my life,</i>

43:51.462 --> 43:53.589
<i>someone who introduced me</i>
<i>to a life journey</i>

43:53.672 --> 43:55.799
<i>completely foreign to my understanding. </i>

43:56.425 --> 43:58.594
<i>And I will admit before all of you,</i>

43:58.677 --> 44:01.430
<i>my tolerance</i>
<i>and acceptance of her took time, </i>

44:01.972 --> 44:04.767
and even now, is more intellectual
than instinctive.

44:05.434 --> 44:09.104
But I will continue to work every day
to try and make myself whole.

44:09.688 --> 44:12.775
And I can only urge all Americans
to look into their own hearts,

44:13.484 --> 44:17.488
<i>where I believe they will find</i>
<i>their own compassion and understanding.</i>

44:18.614 --> 44:20.199
<i>My name is Tom Kirkman, </i>

44:20.282 --> 44:24.203
<i>and I present myself as a candidate</i>
<i>for the presidency of the United States.</i>

44:24.286 --> 44:26.747
Not as a partisan
of the right or the left,

44:27.331 --> 44:30.709
but as one of you,
the frustrated majority of Americans

44:30.793 --> 44:34.296
<i>who just want sensible solutions</i>
<i>to the issues of our time. </i>

44:34.380 --> 44:35.839
<i>In asking for your vote, </i>

44:35.923 --> 44:39.843
<i>I ask you to take this giant leap with me</i>
<i>away from politics as usual</i>

44:40.552 --> 44:42.429
<i>and declare your independence.</i>

44:42.513 --> 44:46.266
Thank you. Good night, and God bless you,

44:46.350 --> 44:48.686
and God bless
these United States of America.

44:48.769 --> 44:51.021
[all cheering]

45:01.698 --> 45:02.533
[Tom] Thank you.

45:02.616 --> 45:06.286
The Moss leak.
It wasn't the lab, and it wasn't me.

45:07.246 --> 45:10.666
I underestimated you.
Don't underestimate me.

45:23.011 --> 45:25.013
[theme music playing]
